Discrete Memoryless Channel

Idealised channel with no memory.

Symbols can be sent. Symbols can be received. Transmitter must identify sent symbols based on the received symbols.

  • A matrix maps the probability of each TX symbol being received as each RX symbols
  • 'a priori' probabilities give the probability of being sent in the first place
  • 'a posteriori' probabilities give the probability that was sent based on

Decision Rules

Question: Suppose is observed at the output. What is the optimum decision rule?

Answer: Want to be the most likely value could have had based on the observation i.e. we want to choose to maximise . This is called the "maximum a posteriori" (MAP) rule.

[Lecture on 1.4]

Minimax Rule

If the a priori probabilities are unknown, we treat them as variables and consider the worst-case set of a priori probabilities for each possible rule, then select the rule with the lowest worst-case probability of error.

Consider a BSC with 0s and 1s - let the a priori probability of 0 be denoted P(0).
There are four possible decision rules - plot the probability of error for each one as a function of P(0). You'll find it's a set of lines in the box [0,0]-[1,1]
The minimax rule is the one with the lowest maximum.

Geometric Representation of Signals

We represent signals as a linear sum of orthonormal basis functions
Orthonormal => orthognonal and normalised

Orthogonal functions: their correlation (intergral of their product from 0 to T) is zero

Normalised: the energy of each signal is 1 (i.e. its correlation with itself is 1)

So two functions and are orthonormal if

The optimum receiver (RHS) can simply mix the signal with each of our basis functions and integrate. Because the basis functions are orthonormal, this will give back the original vector coefficients.

In the absence of noise, this receiver behaves perfectly.

Choosing Signal Vector Constellation

Invariance of Probability of Error to Rotation and Translation of the Constellation:

  • In MAP detection, the probability of error depends only on the Euclidian distance between the points and
  • The additive Gaussian noise vector is a sphere in the signal space
  • Therefore, rotating of translating the entire constellation through signal space has no bearing on the probability of error

Minimum Energy Constellation
Since we can move our constellation around the vector space freely without affecting the probability of error, we should choose the spot with minimum energy.

QPSK

  • Place our signals on a 2D plane evenly distributed around the unit circle
  • Four signals in this case

As always, we use Gray coding to minimise bit errors for the most likely mistakes.

Probability of Bit Error

Suppose there are four signals in a square, Gray-coded. Then:

  • The first bit can flip with probability
  • The second bit can flip with probability
  • In this case, these occur independently because each bit has its own axis in signal space

Bit energy = symbol energy / bits per symbol

Probability of Error
Analysing probability of error along the and axes would make it tricky to determine when it crosses the decision boundary.
Instead. we can consider the noise vector parallel to the decision boundary and the noise vector perpendicular to the decision boundary. These have the same distribution as the horizontal and vertical components, and are independent of one another, so the analysis is the same.
Probability of error is simply the probability that the noise vector along one axis is greater than the distance from to the decision boundary . .

Is this a good approximation?

At high SNR, this is the case (crossing any boundary is unlikely, so crossing two is negligible).

Therefore, at high SNR, the union bound is not much larger than the actual probability of error.

OFDM

Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing

Inter-Symbol Interference (ISI): The channel's impulse response is not a delta function, it has some time spread, potentially quite a large one (caused by multiple paths from TX to RX)

  • One possible solution is a very slow signal (long pulse duration )
  • OFDM suggests sending many such signals on different frequencies

This is a little weird. Start by considering a QAM system:

Let us abstractly represent this by:

where

We can then transmit multiple of these in parallel at different frequencies. The frqeuency spacing must be (not like usual, because of the quadrature signals. Proof left as an exercise).


Note each on the left is a COMPLEX value (the real part being our first signal, and imaginary part our quadrature signal)

Critical practical advantage: creating all these oscillators and keeping them in sync would be a nightmare. However, this setup is very easy to handle in a DSP context using FFT.

[End of lecture on 7.1]
